sed","1269–Female":"1269–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1269":"1269","1266":"1266","Abt 1298":"about 1298","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","Dumbarton Castle,  Scotland,":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Hugh de Danzielstoun was born in 1266, in Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. He married Gilchrist Mure about 1298, in Scotland, United Kingdom. He died in 1317, in Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1266–1317":"1266–1317","1271–Female":"1271–Surnud","1269–Female":"1269–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1269":"1269","1266":"1266","Abt 1298":"umbes 1298","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","Dumbarton Castle,  Scotland,":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1266–1317":"1266–1317","1271–Female":"1271–Kuollut","1269–Female":"1269–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1269":"1269","1266":"1266","Abt 1298":"noin 1298","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","Dumbarton Castle,  Scotland,":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scotland":"Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1266–1317":"1266–1317","1271–Female":"1271–Décédée","1269–Female":"1269–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1269":"1269","1266":"1266","Abt 1298":"environ 1298","1271":"1271","1317":"1317","Dumbarton Castle,  Scotland,":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Scotland":"Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Dumbarton Castle, Strathclyde, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Sir Hugh de Danzielstoun est né en 1266, à Dumbarton, Dunbartonshire, Écosse, Royaume-Uni. Il a épousé Gilchrist Mure environ 1298